elements.content: Three one-dimensional molybdenum oxide/2,2‘-bipyridine species have been prepared by hydrothermal methods and structurally characterized. The reaction of MoO3, 2,2‘-bipyridine, and H2O in the mole ratio 1:0.68:680 at 160 °C for 120 h in a 23 mL Teflon-lined Parr acid digestion bomb produces colorless rods of [MoO3(2,2‘-bipy)] (1) mixed with colorless octahedra of [Mo3O9(2,2‘-bipy)2] (3). The structure of 1 consists of one-dimensional chains of corner-sharing distorted {MoO4N2} octahedra. [Mo2O6(2,2‘-bipy)] (2) was prepared from a mixture of Na2MoO4·2H2O, MoO3, 2,2‘-bipyridine, MnCl2·4H2O, and H2O in the mole ratio 1:1:2:1.9:263 and was isolated as colorless plates. In contrast to the structure of 1, compound 2 consists of a chain of alternating corner-sharing {MoO4N2} octahedra and {MoO4} tetrahedra. Compound 3 was isolated as colorless octahedra. The structure of 3 consists of a chain of corner-sharing {MoO4N2} octahedra and {MoO4} tetrahedra that alternate such that each {MoO4N2} octahedron corner-shares with another such octahedron and a {MoO4} tetrahedron; consequently, each {MoO4} unit corner shares with two {MoO4N2} octahedra. Introduction

Considerable attention has been focused on metal oxide based solid phases due to their applications in catalysis, sorption, molecular electronics, energy storage, optical materials, and ceramics.The evolution of metal oxide chemistry is dependent upon the synthesis of new solids possessing unique structures and properties, although synthesis of these materials remains a challenge.Combining hydrothermal techniques with the structure-directing properties of organic components provides a strategy for the isolation of metastable inorganic/organic composites which retain some structural features of their synthetic precursors. The cooperative assembly of molybdenum oxide/organic phases was first demonstrated with the isolation and characterization of [H3NCH2CH2NH3][Mo3O10]. An extensive structural chemistry for such composite oxide materials was suggested by the subsequent characterization of the one-dimensional phases [H3N(CH2)6NH3][Mo4O13] and Na(NH4)[Mo3O10].

elements.content: Polymeric structures based on infinite one-dimensional chains of oxomolybdenum polyhedra are characteristic of the dimolybdate and trimolybdate systems.However, examination of the structures of [H3NCH2CH2NH3][Mo3O10], K2[Mo3O10], (NH4)2[Mo3O10], and Na(NH4)[Mo3O10]8 and of the related tetramolybdate [H3N(CH2)6NH3][Mo4O13]8 reveals that although all share a common one-dimensional framework, there are marked differences in their polyhedral connectivities. A common thread in the structural chemistry of these species is the occurrence of edge-sharing between adjacent polyhedra as part of their structural motif. Examination of the title compounds reveals the absence of edge-sharing interactions, an observation that can be attributed to the introduction of the bipyridyl ligand which serves to “passivate” the molybdenum oxide coordination sphere by blocking further Mo−oxo bond formation and apparently limiting the aggregation process to corner-sharing linkages.

While crystal “engineering” based on transition-metal coordination to appropriate ligands has evolved dramatically since the seminal work of Robson and Hoskins,applications to metal oxides have remained largely unexplored. Herein, we report the syntheses and structural characterization of a series of inorganic/organic composite materials incorporating 2,2‘-bipyridine components as ligands, represented by three members of the new family of materials [(MoO3) n (2,2‘-bipy) m ]:  [MoO3(2,2‘-bipy)] (1), [Mo2O6(2,2‘-bipy)] (2), and [Mo3O9(2,2‘-bipy)2] (3).

An empirical absorption correction using the program DIFABS was applied to all data, and the data were corrected for Lorentz and polarization effects. The structures were solved by direct methods. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. Hydrogen atoms were placed in calculated positions and were refined isotropically. elements.content: Hydrothermal synthesis, in common with other soft-chemical techniques, has previously been shown to produce a wide variety of metastable oxide materials. Utilization of the hydrothermal method has allowed the isolation of the three organic/inorganic hybrid materials reported herein:  [MoO3(2,2‘-bipy)] (1), [Mo2O6(2,2‘-bipy)] (2), and [Mo3O9(2,2‘-bipy)2] (3). Hydrothermal syntheses of 1−3 were accomplished using Teflon-lined Parr acid digestion bombs as the reaction vessels at temperatures of either 160 or 200 °C and autogenous pressure. Although in our first successful preparation of 1−3 (see Experimental Section, methods A) either FeCl2·4H2O or MnCl2·4H2O were present in the initial reaction mixture, neither were found in the crystalline products as isolated and characterized by SEM. However, attempts to reproduce the syntheses in the absence of these reaction components have met with mixed success, as evidenced by the alternate preparation methods given for 1 and 3. It is not uncommon for necessary reactants in hydrothermal processes to be absent from the product, while their specific role in nucleation or providing a repository of metal clusters remains elusive.

elements.content: As shown in Figure a, the structure of [MoO3(2,2‘-bipy)] (1) consists of one-dimensional chains of corner-sharing {MoO4N2} octahedra. The coordination geometry of each molybdenum is defined by two bridging oxo groups, two terminal oxo groups, and the two pyridyl nitrogen donors of the 2,2‘-bipyridine chelate. The molybdenum site exhibits the two short−two intermediate−two long bond length pattern common to the molybdenum oxides. The long Mo−N bond distances can be attributed to the strong trans influence of the terminal oxo groups. The Mo-bridging oxo group distances are unsymmetrical, giving rise to an infinite {···OMo···OMo} chain, with alternating short−long Mo−O distances of 1.822 and 2.031 Å, respectively.

elements.content: The structure of [Mo2O6(2,2‘-bipy)] (2) is composed of chains of corner-sharing {MoO4N2} octahedra and {MoO4} tetrahedra which alternate to form the one-dimensional chains shown in Figure b. As in 1, the octahedral molybdenum coordination geometry is defined by the two bridging oxo groups, two terminal oxo groups, and the pyridyl nitrogens of the 2,2‘-bipyridine chelate. However, in 2 each molybdenum octahedron corner-shares with two adjacent molybdenum tetrahedra whose coordination geometries are defined by two bridging oxo groups and two terminal oxo groups. In contrast to 1, the bridging oxo groups are symmetrically disposed about each molybdenum site, so that the infinite Mo−O chains appear as alternating two long−two short interactions {···MoOh···OMoTdO···} (where MoOh represents the octahedral molybdenum site and MoTd the tetrahedral site).

elements.content: The structure of [Mo3O9(2,2‘-bipy)2] (3), like that of 2, is composed of corner-sharing {MoO4N2} octahedra and {MoO4} tetrahedra. However, the polyhedra from which 3 is constructed alternate such that the chain repeat sequence is two {MoO4N2} octahedra followed by one {MoO4} tetrahedron, as shown in Figure c. As in 1 and 2, the octahedral molybdenum coordination geometry can be defined by two bridging oxo groups, two terminal oxo groups, and the pyridyl nitrogens of the 2,2‘-bipyridine chelate. The coordination geometry of the tetrahedral molybdenum site in 3, as in 2, is defined by two bridging oxo groups and two terminal oxo groups. Bond distances in 3 are consistent with the trends commonly observed for different molybdenum polyhedral types, with short oxo bridges to the tetrahedral molybdenum sites, relative to the oxo-bridging distances to the octahedral sites.

elements.content: The packing arrangement of 1, seen in Figure , shows the 2,2‘-bipyridine rings of 1 fanning out along the chains. The parallel chains align such that each chain has six neighbors, with no close contacts between adjacent chains. In contrast, examination of the packing of 2 reveals significant Mo···O contact distances of 2.768 Å between adjacent symmetry-related chains. The interactions between the molybdenum atom of a {MoO4} tetrahedron and one of the terminal oxygens of an {MoO4N2} octahedron on a neighboring chain form a virtual dimer of chains as shown in Figure . Finally, the chains that comprise compound 3 show pronounced “ruffling” due to the steric constraints imposed by the {MoO4} tetrahedra present in the structure, as shown in Figure a. While this change of direction in propagation of the chain is also present in 2 (see Figure b), it is more pronounced in 3 due to the increased length of the tether between the {MoO4} sites. Examination of 3 along the crystallographic c axis, as illustrated in Figure b, reveals virtual channels occupied by π-stacked 2,2‘-bipyridine (C−C bonds are drawn as heavy lines for clarity). Removal of the carbon atoms emphasizes the virtual channels shown in Figure c.

elements.content: Despite the extensive real and potential applications of solid-phase metal oxides, the rational synthesis of such materials remains elusive. The synthetic challenge reflects the insolubility and lack of reactivity at low temperatures of the starting materials, coupled to the fact that the solid grows simultaneously in three dimensions. Hydrothermal synthesis provides a low-temperature technique for the synthesis of metastable solid phases which retain the structural integrity of the starting materials. By combining this synthetic methodology with the introduction of organic components, new classes of organic/inorganic hybrid materials are accessible. The organic component serves not only to introduce hydrophilic/hydrophobic interactions that necessitate structural reorganization of the oxide phases but also as conventional ligands occupy sites on the metal coordination sphere so as to “passivate” the surface and “direct” aggregation toward lower dimensional structures.
